article.description: Dee Dee Wheeler also grabbed eight rebounds and had four steals to help Arizona (13-5, 6-3) avenge its 15-point loss to Arizona State on Thursday.
article.headline: Arizona rebounds from loss to Arizona State
article.linkText: Arizona's late run leads to 'gut-check' win vs. Wisconsin
article.story:
MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A strong finish was exactly what the doctor
ordered for 19th-ranked Arizona Sunday.

	   Dee-Dee Wheeler scored 23 points, and the Wildcats, who had two
starters battling illness, ended the game on a 9-2 run to defeat
Wisconsin 62-55 in a non-conference game.

	   "I thought it was a real gut-check for our team,'' said Arizona
coach Joan Bonvicini.

	   Arizona (13-5) also got 13 points from Julie Brase and a
career-high 12 from Natalie Jones.

	   Stephanie Rich scored 13 points to lead Wisconsin (4-14), which
shot just 32 percent (17-of-53) from the floor.

	   Arizona played the entire game without starter Aimee Grzyb, who
didn't make the trip because of an undisclosed illness. Grzyb, a
guard, averages 12.4 points per game.

	   Meanwhile, the Wildcats' leading scorer and rebounder,
Shawntinice Polk, didn't start the second half because she felt ill
at halftime.

	   Polk eventually returned but got in foul trouble and fouled out
with 5:41 remaining. She finished with nine points and six
rebounds.

	   But others stepped up for the Wildcats.

	   Brase's third 3-pointer of the game gave Arizona a 56-53 lead
with 2:40 left.

	   And Wheeler made sure that lead stood, hitting 5-of-6 free
throws in the final 2:29 to hold Wisconsin at bay.

	   "Lately, we haven't been hitting our free throws, but luckily
this game we finished great hitting our free throws,'' Wheeler
said. "I think it was a great finish.''

	   It was a poor finish for Wisconsin, which led much of the game
and appeared headed for an upset and a third victory in four games.
But the Badgers couldn't overcome their poor shooting from the
floor despite a perfect 17-of-17 showing from the free throw line.

	   "We thought it could be a shot heard round the world,'' said
Wisconsin coach Jane Albright. "But when it got tough, they were a
little tougher.''

	   The wear and tear of playing four games in eight days finally
caught up with the Badgers, who didn't score a field goal in the
final 3:29 of the game.

	   "We just didn't have it in us to finish it off,'' Albright
said.

	   Wisconsin's Kristi Seeger hit a pair of free throws with 3:05
remaining to tie the game at 53-53, but the Wildcats followed
Brase's 3-pointer by forcing a turnover.

	   Wheeler then hit two free throws to make it 58-53 with 2:29
left.

	   Wisconsin got within 59-55 after Rich hit two free throws with
42.9 seconds left, but Wheeler was 3-of-4 from the free throw line
in the final 36.4 seconds to seal the victory.

	   "This is a real big win,'' Bonvicini said. "The Big Ten's a
real good conference ... so to get a win on the road, a really
quality win, is important for our team.''

	   After a strong start, the Wildcats went cold.

	   They scored 10 points in the opening 3:22, but had just 13 the
rest of the half.

	   Wisconsin, meanwhile, missed eight of its first nine shots from
the floor, but answered with a 17-4 run and took a 27-23 lead into
halftime.

	   Emily Ashbaugh added 11 points and Ashley Josephson 10 for
Wisconsin.
